rlisle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from the Cumbrian city of Carlisle, in whose name Celtic <i>cair</i> ‘fort’ has been compounded with the Romano-British name of the settlement, <i>Luguvalium</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Carlile","meanings":["English: variant of   Carlisle  ."]},{"name":"Carlyle","meanings":["English (Cumberland) and Scottish (Dumfriesshire): variant of   Carlisle  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":8,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":39,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":64,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William de Carlisle was born about 1251, in Carlisle, Cumberland, England as the son of Sir William of Carlisle. He had at least 1 daughter with Margaret De Brus. He died in March 1329, in Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, at the age of 79."},"et":{"about 1251–March 1329":"umbes 1251–märts 1329","1251–1329":"1251–1329","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1287–1367":"1287–1367","1224–Male":"1224–Surnud","March 1329":"märts 1329","1251":"1251","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","1367":"1367","1287":"1287","1265":"1265","about 1287":"umbes 1287","about 1251":"umbes 1251","1329":"1329","1317":"1317","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Carlisle, Cumberland, England":"Carlisle, Cumberland, England","Annandale, Dumfriesshire, Scotland.":"Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1251–March 1329":"noin 1251–maaliskuu 1329","1251–1329":"1251–1329","1265–Female":"1265–Kuollut","1287–1367":"1287–1367","1224–Male":"1224–Kuollut","March 1329":"maaliskuu 1329","1251":"1251","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","1367":"1367","1287":"1287","1265":"1265","about 1287":"noin 1287","about 1251":"noin 1251","1329":"1329","1317":"1317","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Carlisle, Cumberland, England":